  "prompt": "Whom was Muhammad worshipping before getting revelations?",
  "response": "Before receiving revelations, Prophet Muhammad is traditionally understood to have adhered to a form of monotheism known as **Hanifism**. The term \"Hanif\" refers to individuals who maintained the worship of one God, rejecting the prevalent polytheistic practices of the Arabian Peninsula at the time.\n\n### Context of Pre-Revelation Arabia\n\n- **Polytheistic Environment**: Mecca, Muhammad's hometown, was a center of polytheism with the Kaaba housing numerous idols representing various deities. The Quraysh tribe, to which Muhammad belonged, were prominent caretakers of these idols and actively engaged in polytheistic rituals.\n  \n- **Hanif Beliefs**: Hanifs were people who, influenced by Abrahamic traditions, sought to return to the pure monotheistic worship of one God. They rejected idol worship and other polytheistic practices common in their society. Although not formally organized into a distinct religious group, Hanifs represented a strand of monotheistic belief that predated Islam.\n\n### Muhammad's Personal Beliefs\n\n- **Personal Inclination**: Historical accounts and Islamic tradition suggest that Muhammad was personally inclined towards monotheism from a young age. He is often described as contemplative and spiritually inclined, seeking a deeper understanding of God beyond the surrounding polytheistic norms.\n  \n- **Rejection of Polytheism**: Even before his prophethood, Muhammad is believed to have rejected the idol worship that was customary in Mecca. This is evidenced by various stories from his early life, such as the famous incident where he cleared the Kaaba of idols in his later prophetic mission, symbolizing a long-held commitment to monotheism.\n\n### Transition to Prophethood\n\n- **Receiving Revelations**: At the age of 40, Muhammad began receiving revelations from Allah (God) through the angel Gabriel. These revelations, which continued for approximately 23 years, constituted the Quran and laid the foundations for Islam.\n  \n- **Mission to Restore Monotheism**: Muhammad's prophetic mission was seen as a continuation and culmination of the monotheistic traditions he already espoused, aiming to re-establish pure worship of one God and eliminate idolatry.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nIn summary, before receiving divine revelations, Muhammad was inclined towards monotheism as a Hanif, rejecting the polytheistic practices prevalent in his society. His early beliefs set the stage for the emergence of Islam, which formalized these monotheistic principles into a comprehensive and enduring religious tradition.\n\n**References:**\n- \"Muhammad: Man and Prophet\" by Adil Salahi.\n- \"The Life of the Prophet Muhammad\" by Ibn Ishaq.\n- Islamic historical sources and teachings from Sunni and Shia traditions.",
